04330nam a22006135i 9780773555426DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735554267 a10.1515/97807735554262doi  a(DE-B1597)657108  a(OCoLC)1049912016  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNA1333.S6b.C453 2018 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a720.924223  aLI 84220qDE-14/sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/97141:1 aSiza, Álvaro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeasure of the West :bA Representation of Travel /cGiovanni Chiaramonte, Álvaro Siza. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b60 drawings, 40 colour photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTrue Things -- tLandscape, Everything Our Eyes Perceive: Ecce Homo -- tTravel Drawings -- tItaly -- tFrance -- tGreece -- tAustria -- tMexico -- tIndex of Drawings -- tBiographies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1984, Giovanni Chiaramonte photographed Álvaro Siza's building in Berlin, on whose façade some young people had written Bonjour Tristesse. The image was published on the cover of the magazine Lotus International. The following year, Siza and Chiaramonte met in Évora, on the occasion of a new series by the Italian photographer featuring the buildings of the great Portuguese architect. It marked the beginning of a long friendship and a shared reflection on architecture, photography, and urban life. The Measure of the West presents a selection of sixty drawings by Siza and forty photographs taken by Chiaramonte in cities around the world. They make up two parallel routes that lead to the discovery of the shape of the modern city – always hanging in the balance between proportion, in which civilization can develop, and disproportion, in which civilization can go astray. Although animated by different intentions, these sketches and photographs appear as coherent traces of the same design, guided by the same desire to see, discover, understand, and learn. The differences between the black and white strokes of the drawings and the colour of the photographs disappear. Short texts, including thoughts on architecture, photography, drawing, representation, and nature, enrich a "poem of change" taking place in an era of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitectural photography. 0aArt and architecture. 0aCities and towns in art. 0aCities and townsvPictorial works. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aChiaramonte, Giovanni, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCremascoli, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiza, Álvaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZardini, Mirko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773555426?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555426/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles